                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>CAB AIR RELEASE</title>
                    <para>The cab air release control permits the driver to deflate the air springs from the cab when
                        hooking up to a trailer. For normal operation, the air suspension cab control switch will be in
                        the RUN position (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0301002">Figure 2</hotlnk>). To dump the air from the springs, place the valve
                        in the DUMP position. The switch has a guard to prevent an unintentional air dump.
                        <emph type="bold">Do not remove the guard.</emph>
                        An instrument panel warning light indicates when the cab control switch is in the DUMP position.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0301002" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0301002" filename="../figg03/G0301002.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 2. Cab Air Release Control</caption>
                    </figure>
                </lev1>
                <lev1>
                    <title>HEIGHT CONTROL VALVE</title>
                    <para>The height control valve (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0301003">Figure 3</hotlnk>) is the brain of the air suspension and is sensitive
                        to height. When properly adjusted, it will provide and maintain ride height.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0301003" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g0301003" filename="../figg03/G0301003.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3. Height Control Valve</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1.TO AIR BAGS</callout1>
                            <callout1>2.FROM INVERSION VALVE</callout1>
                            <callout1>3.CENTERING PIN HOLES</callout1>
                            <callout1>4.END OF ROD TO BE FLUSH WITH FLAT EDGE OF VALVE</callout1>
                            <callout1>5.CAPSCREW [TORQUE 15 FT-LBS. (20 N&#8226;M)]</callout1>
                            <callout1>6.CENTER PUNCH MARK TO BE TOWARD LINK END OF ROD</callout1>
                            <callout1>7.LEVER ARM IN NEUTRAL POSITION</callout1>
                            <callout1>8.RUBBER LINK</callout1>
                            <callout1>9.CLAMP</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <para>The height control valve is mounted at the rear of vehicle frame. The valve has a lever arm
                        connected to the rear axle assembly with a vertical linkage rod. This height control valve is
                        sensitive to frame height, thus providing automatic filling or exhausting of the air springs to
                        keep the vehicle level.
                    </para>
                    <para>The lever arm neutral position feature (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0301003">Figure 3</hotlnk>) is also incorporated in the valve and serves to
                        automatically return the valve to a closed position. The height control valve is closed in the
                        neutral position.
                    </para>
                </lev1>
